Claude 4.8 on 2026-06-29 at ~17:10:

Gold: promoted sun-gold into iteration 16's own source (all three files) and deleted the temporary golds folder (you're right — those weren't interaction files; I shouldn't have used that name).

Tuta: redrawn from the new dotted capture. Pulled the 20 black dots, sorted them by height and assigned each per your legend (4 leg bases → triangle lower vertex → 2 valley-base → valley → 2 interior peaks → 4 peak tops → triangle right vertex → 2 rectangle lower → triangle top vertex → 2 rectangle top). The data came out clean and symmetric (both legs 8 px wide, both peak-tops 7, valley base 5), mapped uniformly into the box. Rendered side by side with the old one and Telegram — even sticks, a valley at its true depth, a full roof bar; it now reads like the real mark.

Illumination — the physics. Model a point lamp at height 1 directly over the plane; a flat patch at horizontal distance x catches light by two factors: inverse-square (1/d², d²=1+x²) and Lambert's cosine law (a flat patch collects ∝ cosθ, cosθ = 1/d). So E(x) = cosθ/d² = 1/(1+x²)^{3/2} — the classic "floor under a lamp" curve, peaked at the core with a soft tail (unlike the current flat-core/hard-rim look). E(0)=1, E(1)=2^{-3/2}≈0.354; to clip to 0 at the reach x=1 while keeping the shape I subtract that rim value and renormalise:

  f(x) = ( (1+x²)^{-3/2} − 2^{-3/2} ) / ( 1 − 2^{-3/2} ),  x∈[0,1].

Implementation. Refactored the point glow: the falloff is now a single swappable `glowFalloff(s)` (s = r/R) feeding `radialGlow` (renamed from radialQuad), with f(0)=1 and f(1)=0 so the reach stays pinned at R for every curve — that's how the four variants keep an identical clip and compare fairly. Base iteration 16 keeps the current curve until you pick.

Four runnable comparison copies (NOT interaction files — temporary, named plainly), in `sources/iteration16/lighting-options/`:
  1-current    f = 1 − s²                              (what the site uses now)
  2-linear     f = 1 − s                               (the earlier linear decay)
  3-physical   f = ((1+s²)^-1.5 − 2^-1.5)/(1 − 2^-1.5) (inverse-square × Lambert, h=1)
  4-alt        f = 2/(1+s²) − 1                        (isotropic inverse-square — a mote catching light from all sides, no cosine: fuller, longer halo)
All share the same reach and the same core brightness. `falloff-curves.png` (the four profiles) and `glow-preview.png` (the four glows rendered) are in that folder; the preview shows 3 and 4 reading as a luminous core with a natural soft halo vs the current flat disc. Once you pick, I'll fold that falloff into the base source and delete the folder.

